This is a Godot 4.6 project using GDScript (not C#).

Project context:
- This is a learning project — a simple memory match 
  card game (4x4 grid, flip pairs, match to win)
- I am a developer (PHP, JavaScript, React background) 
  new to Godot specifically
- Target platform: Windows desktop

Conventions:
- snake_case for variables, functions, and file names
- PascalCase for node names, classes, and scene files
- Use signals for cross-node communication, not direct 
  references where avoidable
- Prefer composition over deep inheritance
- Project structure:
  - /scenes for .tscn files
  - /scripts for .gd files  
  - /assets for any sprites, sounds, fonts (none needed 
    for this project — use ColorRect or simple shapes)

When editing:
- Don't refactor unrelated code
- Don't add features I didn't ask for
- If a node path or signal is unclear, ask before guessing
- Match the existing code style in the file you're editing
- Make minimal changes — surgical fixes, not rewrites

Teaching mode:
- I know how to code; I don't know Godot's specifics yet
- When you tell me to do something in the Godot editor 
  (create a node, set a property), be specific: which 
  panel, what to click, what to name it
- Explain GDScript-specific syntax that differs from 
  Python/JavaScript when it first appears

Working style for this project:
- Use targeted edits, not full file rewrites, when 
  modifying existing code
- When explaining Godot concepts, keep explanations to 
  2-3 sentences max — I'll ask follow-ups if I need more
- For each phase, complete one phase fully before 
  asking if you should continue
- Always tell me explicitly which file you're creating 
  or editing
- After completing work, give me a 1-line "what to test" 
  instruction

Scope discipline:
- This is a learning project — keep code clear over 
  clever
- No optimization passes unless I ask
- No "production-ready" patterns (object pools, state 
  machines) unless the feature genuinely needs them
- Comments should explain *why*, not *what*